\begin_layout Section
The Simulation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We use cosmological N-body simulations called the Bolshoi simulation and
 the MultiDark simulation, described in XXX and XXX respectively, to investigate
 the maximum circular velocity dependence of halo clustering.
 The Bolshoi simulation uses 
\begin_inset Formula $2048^{3}$
\end_inset

 particles with a volume of 
\begin_inset Formula $(250$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $h^{-1}{\rm Mpc})^{3}$
\end_inset

, while the MultiDark simulation uses the same number of particles as the
 Bolshoi simulation but with a volume of (
\begin_inset Formula $1h^{-1}{\rm Gpc})^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 Both simulations assumes a flat 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda{\rm CDM}$
\end_inset

 model with density parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{m}=0.27$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{\Lambda}=0.73$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{b}=0.0469$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{8}=0.82$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $n=0.95$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $h=0.70$
\end_inset

.
 (??Do I need to put a name for each constant?)The details of the simulations
 are described in XXX.
 For halo identification, we use the ROCKSTAR halo finder (XXX) where the
 halo masses and maximum circular velocities are computed from bound particles.
 
\end_layout

