\begin_layout Standard
In other words, the above equation is a one to one mapping between the virial
 mass of the halo and its maximum circular velocity.
 Given this mapping, we can translate clustering measurements as a function
 of halo mass into predicted clustering measurements as a function of maximum
 circular velocity.
 Our goal below is to determine whether this conversion describes the measured
 clustering or if there is a residual dependence on the maximum circular
 velocity.
 In order to explore this, we first split the sample into a sequence of
 virial mass bins, chosen such that there are the same numbers of halos
 in each bin.
 This process is reminiscent of an abundance-matching procedure (cite XXX).
 We then further split each bin into two subsamples with their observed
 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max,obs}}$
\end_inset

 greater than (denoted by 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

upper
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) or less than (denoted as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

lower
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}(M_{{\rm vir}})$
\end_inset

.
 This selection ensures that both the upper and lower subsamples have the
 same mean halo mass.
 Therefore, in the absence of an additional 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

 dependence (??isn't this 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir}}$
\end_inset

 dependence?) on clustering, these samples should have the same clustering
 properties.
 Note that this would not be true if we had simply split the sample along
 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

, since the two resulting subsamples would have different mean halo masses.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to measure halo biases, we compute halo-matter cross correlation
 functions for each subsample and measure a linear bias 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
b_{lin}=<\xi_{hm}(r)/\xi_{mm}(r)>,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{hm}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{mm}$
\end_inset

 are halo-matter and matter-matter correlation functions and we take the
 average of the ratio on 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $10h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $20h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

 (??may change to jackknife samplings).
 Here, instead of using full DM particles, we subsample 
\begin_inset Formula $1000000$
\end_inset

 particles to compute matter auto correlation functions.
 The reason we use cross correlation functions is to reduce the shot noise
 effect on the error.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:linear-bias"

\end_inset

, we show how linear biases depend on the maximum circular velocity as a
 function of halo mass.
 We compute linear biases for each mass bin classifying into 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

upper
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

lower
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 maximum circular velocity halos.
 The halos which have different maximum circular velocity clearly cluster
 differently.
 Furthermore, the relative bias of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

upper
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 versus 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

lower
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 subsamples increases with decreasing halo mass to almost 40% on low mass
 end.
\end_layout

