\begin_layout Standard
In Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:small-scale"

\end_inset

, we investigate the maximum circular velocity dependence of halo bias on
 small scales.
 On small scales, a halo bias is scale-dependent.
 The question here is whether halos with different maximum circular velocity
 have dierent scale-dependence on their biases.
 In order to nd that, we take the ratio of halo-matter cross correlation
 functions between 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

upper" and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

lower" subsamples and normalize it by their linear biases.
 Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:small-scale"

\end_inset

 clearly shows that the scale-dependence depends on the maximum circular
 velocity and its Vmax-dependence is mass-dependent.
 As halo mass decreases, the relative scale-dependence between 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

upper" and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

lower" subsamples increases, especially halos with large maximum circular
 velocities heavily clustered around 
\begin_inset Formula $1h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

